<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7354&amp;p=72419#p72419"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">tomaitheous wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />What I want to know is, when you view the signal on a scope - should it be under a match &lt;n&gt; ohm load - in that context?<br /></div>If you want the voltages to be per the standard, yes, you should put a matching load on.<div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Or will the receiver take care of scaling to appling the new voltage levels on its side,<br /></div>Some will, some won't. For example, RF modulated video normalizes the video signal and can deal with this.<div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />and the reference to the composite specifications (sync, blank, peak) are for the signal <em>without</em> the load put on the signal, for the scope?<br /></div> Well, what matters is that the receiving device get e.g. 0.7V for full white. If the driver expected a 75 ohm load, the receiver should be a 75 ohm load for the voltage to be what is intended. On the other hand, without a transmission line, you can ignore it and you won't get reflections. Just looking at the unloaded output with a scope will probably be 2x what you'd see when properly loaded (for a correct driver) but who knows if they did use the correct drive impedance?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3512">lidnariq</a> — Fri Jan 07, 2011 12:43 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
