<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7354&amp;p=72414#p72414"><![CDATA[
lidnariq: Thanks <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" title="Very Happy" /><br /><br /> I have another question though. Composite input should have a 75 ohm load to ground on the receiving side, so transmission should be higher voltage range than what the receiver will decode. While I don't particularly understand the math behind it, matching a 75 ohm impedance cable to a 75 ohm resistor load (a mismatch causes problem), helps remove reflections of high frequencies back into the line(to removing ringing/ghosting/etc). I understand the logic (and how impedance works). What I want to know is, when you view the signal on a scope - should it be under a match &lt;n&gt; ohm load - in that context? Or will the receiver take care of scaling to appling the new voltage levels on its side, and the reference to the composite specifications (sync, blank, peak) are for the signal <em>without</em> the load put on the signal, for the scope?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3645">tomaitheous</a> — Thu Jan 06, 2011 6:37 pm</p><hr />
