<div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">tomaitheous wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The PCE has Y, R-Y and B-Y and separate CB output pins. Since Cr and Cb aren't summed, all I should have to do with build a four diode bridge rectifier to demodulate each of the two lines. Then apply a light low pass filter.<br /></div>Careful -- you'll need an active rectifier, not a passive one; a conventional 4-diode full-wave rectifier will, even if you use Schottky diodes, drop the center .4V out of your 1Vpp signal.</div><br /><br /> Thanks for the tip. So you mean a 0.4v in the form of a shift/offset or do you mean the whole range will be scaled resulting in the difference? (I think the latter. 'Cause there's a voltage drop a diode?)<br /><br /> Also, I found this link: <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://zone.ni.com/devzone/cda/tut/p/id/4750">http://zone.ni.com/devzone/cda/tut/p/id/4750</a><!-- m --> . It states sync to white level is 1v. White level, not peak level. Peak level is listed as 120 IRE for NTSC-U and 133 IRE for PAL. Funny thing about NTSC-J, is that it shares the same IRE 0 for black starting point. So maybe Peak level for NTSC-J is the same as PAL too. This still doesn't answer some questions. If IRE 100 is in face 0.714v and sync+IRE 100 = 1v, then IRE 120 or 133 pushes the max range past 1v (assuming sync level stays the same). Or is IRE 120/133 the max 0.714 level? <br /><br /> Which leads me to another question. How to represent <em>whiter than white</em> on a RGB 24bit? Do you simply scale down and adjust for this (which makes the whole range darker)? Or do you decode YCrCb at those values, THEN clamp to 0 or 255? I'm thinking it's the latter. You might not be able to show Luma only whiter-than-white, but it should effect the color decoding of the other two channels.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3645">tomaitheous</a> — Tue Jan 04, 2011 12:55 pm</p><hr />
