<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7354&amp;p=72304#p72304"><![CDATA[
Hey Chris. Thanks for verifying that SuperCDROM composite out <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br /> Also, not just s-video out. But component as well. I'm a little wet behind the ears for analog EE, but I pick up things fairly quickly as I move along. The PCE has Y, R-Y and B-Y and separate CB output pins. Since Cr and Cb aren't summed, all I should have to do with build a four diode bridge rectifier to demodulate each of the two lines. Then apply a light low pass filter. The 90 degree phase difference of one of the Chroma out lines won't matter, since it's AM that I'm demodulating at this point. Luma is already there by itself and the IRE level is 0 to 100 (component NTSC-U uses this range compared to composite NTSC-U), so nothing to do on that end. Hopefully that's all I need to do. We'll see how the component output looks when I get some more video amps. (Building the s-video circuit first)<br /><br /> Edit: Also verified composite output from the back pins of my white PCE. It has the same Luma levels as the SGX; 0.0v to 0.84v. So it's not just my SGX (or a specific broken resistor/amp issue).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3645">tomaitheous</a> — Tue Jan 04, 2011 2:11 am</p><hr />
